                                                Korrespondentenkreis</term>
                                </keywords>
                        </textClass></profileDesc><revisionDesc><listChange><change><date>2018-03-14T09:45:20Z</date> | <name>Sascha Grabsch</name> | <orgName>Telota</orgName> | OxGarage DOCX to TEI | 2.15.0</change><change><date>2018-03-14T15:34:57+01:00</date> | <name>Sascha Grabsch</name> | <orgName>Telota</orgName> | convert_tei_file.py | 0.85</change></listChange></revisionDesc></teiHeader><text><body><div type="writingSession"><opener><dateline><pb/> 1 Modena Villas<lb/>April 26<hi rendition="#sup">th</hi>/67.</dateline><salute>My dear Dada,</salute></opener><p>Just as <seg type="comment"><orig>your letter</orig><note xml:id="nekt_pbg_lfb"><ref target="mega_ep4_lzy_3fb">Marx an E. Marx und
                                                  Familie Marx, zw. 13. u.
                                                26.4.1867</ref>.</note></seg> came <seg type="comment"><orig>I was declaring that I thought
                                                  you never could stay away a whole fortnight
                                                  without writing, &amp; that I never would forgive
                                                  you,</orig><note xml:id="fa9996cd-cc45-4add-ad96-9562e011932e">Siehe <ref target="B00252"><?oxy_comment_start author="reichhoff" timestamp="20180502T145509+0200" comment="(Br. 241a.67–68)."?>P.
                                                  Lafargue an Marx, nach dem
                                                  23.4.1867<?oxy_comment_end?></ref> („Je n’ai pas
                                                  besoin de vous donner de nouvelles de votre
                                                  famlille ...“).</note></seg> but my rage began to
                                        evaporate amazingly quickly as soon as your letter was read,
                                        &amp; now I'm actually writing to you.</p><p>I have not as I used to do looked in the beds for you, but I constantly
                                        sing <seg type="comment"><orig><?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?>„Oh!
                                                  would I were a bird that I might to thee &amp;
                                                  breathe a loving word to one so dear to
                                                  me“<?oxy_custom_end?><?oxy_comment_start author="lindenberg" timestamp="20181005T114724+0200" comment="meinerseits nicht nachgewiesen"?>.<?oxy_comment_end?></orig><note xml:id="c945ce7f-690b-4021-9bf7-efbe9e6f75d9">Erste Zeilen aus einer englischen
                                                  Broadside-Ballade. Broadside-Balladen – die
                                                  in England seit dem 16. bis zum etwa Ende des
                                                  19. Jahrhunderts verbreiteten Volks- bzw.
                                                  Straßenlieder, deren Texte auf Blättern
                                                  unterschiedlicher Länge veröffentlicht wurden, mit
                                                  dem Hinweis auf eine bekannte Melodie.
                                                </note></seg>
                                        <seg type="comment"><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648"><orig>Paul</orig></persName><note xml:id="e74e36f2-66fc-4ec0-8764-77a4cc25c135"><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648">Paul
                                                  Lafargue</persName>.</note></seg> has been keeping
                                        me in books, he got me <seg type="comment"><orig><persName key="ed_nkh_xq2_ldb">Cooper's</persName>
                                                  <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-I2PQJKBL">Deerslayer</bibl>, <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-IR8N7UXH">Homeward Bound</bibl>, <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-DB4PJI6W">Eve
                                                  Effingham</bibl>, &amp; I am going to read the
                                                  <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-JFNJFPZW">„Waterwitch“</bibl> &amp; <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-6EWQWNQZ">Two
                                                  admirals</bibl></orig><note xml:id="dab99e38-c7e8-400f-a2fe-ef4627207f2b">Eleanor Marx nennt die Werke von James Fenimore
                                                  Coopers <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-I2PQJKBL">„The Deerslayer“</bibl>, <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-IR8N7UXH">„Homeward Bound“</bibl>, <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-DB4PJI6W">„Eve Effingham“</bibl> (auch u. d. T. „Home as
                                                  Found“), <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-JFNJFPZW">„The Water Witch“</bibl>, <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-6EWQWNQZ">„The Two Admirals“</bibl>.</note></seg>. You see
                                        I'm quite „going the hog“. <seg type="comment"><orig>We had
                                                  £ 5 sent us from the Cape</orig><note xml:id="a8c80e4e-0f9c-477b-8dc7-e33fa3b6781a">In
                                                  Capetown wohnte Marx’ Schwester <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002425">Louise</persName>
                                                  mit ihrem Mann <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002421">Carel
                                                  Juta</persName>.</note></seg>
                                        <pb/> which was a very agreeable surprise. I have not
                                        arranged your books yet, but I'm going to tomorrow. <seg type="comment"><orig>„The Knight of the Rueful
                                                  Countenance“</orig><note xml:id="e609eee1-e185-43e3-956f-5f2d2b10b600">Gemeint ist <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648">Paul
                                                  Lafargue</persName>. – Anspielung auf den Beinamen
                                                  („El Caballero de la Triste Figura“,) den sich die
                                                  Titelgestalt in Miguel de Cervantes Saavedras
                                                  Roman <bibl sameAs="zotero-604880-CPUNY5ZM">„El ingenioso hidalgo Don Quixote
                                                  de la Mancha“</bibl> selbst gibt.</note></seg>, is
                                        looking more rueful than ever because his holidays are up
                                        next week.</p><p><seg type="comment"><orig>On Good Friday</orig><note xml:id="adc17bb7-f34e-41b2-add6-18ae5215feb8">19. April 1867.</note></seg> I eat 16 <seg type="comment"><orig>hot cross buns,</orig><note xml:id="f0194698-7841-471f-a69a-d689c13edd96">Traditionelles Gebäck zum Karfreitag in
                                                  England.</note></seg>
                                        <seg type="comment"><orig><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003076">Laura</persName></orig><note xml:id="c16d7b6d-6d56-412c-a84a-89c393f88960"><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003076">Laura
                                                  Marx</persName>.</note></seg> &amp; <seg type="comment"><orig><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003074">Jenny</persName></orig><note xml:id="e8ecfa39-d3e9-4b01-8058-4767db2a47e5"><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003074">Jenny
                                                  Marx</persName> (Tochter).</note></seg> eat 8.
                                                <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000001635">Louisa</persName>, &amp; Percy <choice>
                                                <sic>Frieligrath</sic>
                                                <corr cert="high"><persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000001632">Freiligrath</persName></corr>
                                        </choice> came here the other day &amp; <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000001632">Percy</persName>
                                        jumped out of the window on the first landing, because I
                                        said he could not, &amp; he wrote me that he would jump out
                                        again if I asked him to. <seg type="comment"><orig><persName key="ed_why_c2g_jfb">Tommy</persName>, <persName key="ed_hdf_p2g_jfb">Blacky</persName> &amp;
                                                  <persName key="ed_mjs_1fg_jfb">Whisky</persName></orig><note xml:id="e0e78d04-2275-4855-8992-bce9fa88cebf">Haustiere in der Familie Marx.</note></seg> send
                                        their compliments. <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648">Paul</persName> &amp; <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003076">Laura</persName> have
                                        had three riding lessons. <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000003076">Laura</persName> looks
                                        very nice in her riding habit, &amp; <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648">Paul</persName> looks
                                        a little shaky. The days after the lessons however both were
                                        rather <hi rendition="#u">stiff</hi> &amp; I had to make
                                                <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002648">Paul</persName> a cushion to rest his bruised
                                        behind upon. I was much <pb/> surprised to receive <seg type="comment"><orig>a letter from <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002614">Franziska</persName>.</orig><note xml:id="cf9eae8a-e7e1-46ec-8989-464e5adb717a">Der
                                                  Brief von <persName key="pdrPo.001.004.000002614">Franzisca Kugelmann</persName> an Eleanor Marx,
                                                  geschrieben vor dem 26. April 1867, konnte
                                                  nicht ermittelt werden.</note></seg></p><p>Now dear Dady goodbye</p><closer>Believe me<lb/>Your <hi rendition="#uu">un</hi>dutyful<lb/>daughter<lb/><hi rendition="#u">Eleanor</hi> </closer></div></body></text></TEI>